@node overview "EASys!, ©'1998 by Thomas Neidhardt: References Overview ..."
@prev main

   @{" < " link main} @{b}EASys! Wizards@{ub}

        ©'98 Thomas Neidhardt, 91058 Erlangen, GERMANY
____________________________________________________________________


   @{b}Overview:@{ub}

   * First in the history of the AMIGA there is a center @{b}SysDataBase@{ub}
     for all important System-References.

     With the introduction of the Directory ENV:RefTable, which
     implements a way of "Registry". The References which are located
     there are recommended to have standardized Names and will contain the
     System and user specific references to Commands, Applications and
     ways of their kind of Application-Start. Thus, @{b}Application-Calls
     will have unique names on each EASys!-System @{ub}but will result
     in the User's preferred Applications or Processes.

     Thus, within this system, the User's Web-Browser will be started
     on each installation through supplying

     @{i}${RefTable/Net-Browser}@{ui}

     in the Shell or to a Shell- or ARexx-Script, even if on System 1
     the User prefers AWeb while on System 2 the User prefers IBrowse.
     Each get's the same result with the same Commandline. In this
     way, the System is perfectly transparent and standardizable for
     the AMIGA (proposal to ICOA as well as to Haage&Partner !).


     @{b}The RefTable may be configured,@{ub} using:

     @{" + " SYSTEM "run <>NIL: ${RefTable/Prefs-RefTable}"} EASys!:Prefs/ReferencePrefs = @{i}${RefTable/Prefs-RefTable}@{ui}



   * The system becomes @{b}fully customizable@{ub} to each user's
     System-Directory-Environment:

     Any EASys!-Script needs to be edited to make it run on your system.
     Just check the ENV-Variables in the EASys!-Reference-Table once
     included with the Installation Process to fit your System and
     Binary-locations. Most of which you still need to configure yourself,
     are programmed to pop up the Reference Editor automatically when
     they are called. Thus, there is no need for you to work through
     all references!

     For this task, the EASys!_ReferencePrefs are delivered with
     the package. The most important References will be configured
     interactively in the Installation-Process.

     Make use of the Table in all your own Shell and Rexx-Scripts as
     well, thus you will never again encounter troubles with
     Shell/Rexx-scripts when rearranging your System's directories!


____________________________________________________________________
@endnode


@node GUI "EASys!, ©'1998 by Thomas Neidhardt: Refrences Editor ..."
@prev main

   @{" < " link main} @{b}EASys! Wizards@{ub}

        ©'98 Thomas Neidhardt, 91058 Erlangen, GERMANY
____________________________________________________________________



   @{b}Using the ReferencePrefs@{ub}

   Each Reference represents a Commandline (CLI-) for starting a
   program, a Shell- or a Rexx-procedure. References ending by
   "-opts" provide Commandline-Options for the referenced Program.

   E.g.:  ${RefTable/Text-Editor-Starter} may be used

   in every Script, and out of every Application's Rexx Port in
   order to run the User-defined specific Text-Editor Start-Procedure.

   The Contents of each Reference will automatically affect
   every Rexx, Shell script as well as many program configuration
   files that make use of them. Thus, when changing a Reference
   later, you will never need to adapt any script or configuration
   anymore, that uses References.


   When pressing the "find.." button, a filerequester will be started
   which serves for assigning your local program to the selected
   Reference. When having pointed to the appropriate program, it's
   reference will be accomplished by an automatically detected calling
   procedure for the program:

   Automatic calling procedure for files:

     having an own icon (.info): "EASys!_bin:wbrun "
     with a suffix ".rexx":      "rx "
     with a suffix ".script":    "execute "

   Here, "wbrun" will start the program as if it was started by
   double clicking onto it's Workbench icon, thus starting it including
   it's Icon ToolTypes.

   Please read all given information in the program's Reference
   requester carefully! If there is an example for a program which
   is generally known for an own icon, but the example shows that it
   is called without "wbrun", remove the automatically detected
   "wbrun" call. This may be recommended due to usability terms,
   as for example that it would be of disadvantage to start the
   program asynchronously.



   When editing a reference and you should doubt about what should
   be entered there, just keep it as is and reconfigure
   this reference later, when you know more about it.

   ToolManager, the famous Toolbar-Commodity and ScreenTab, a really
   sophisticated StartMenu for the AMIGA will understand those
   References  ${RefTable/...} directly, configured as
   a SHELL-Commandline.

   It is recommended to keep the Names of all References standardized
   over all systems, thus providing unique references with perfectly
   embedded User-Choices.. (I will suggest this system at ICOA and
   Haage&Partner).


____________________________________________________________________
@endnode

